		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71fa1fc682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>7:13.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Subjects of expert testimony—Vehicle speed</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<?page no="199"?>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Both expert and lay witnesses may give an opinion about the speed of a moving vehicle,[<footnote.reference refid="I78b6aa6074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] even though the witness made no speed estimate and formed no opinion at the time of observation.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78b6aa6174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>A witness may base his opinion on seeing the vehicle headlights and hearing the noise of the motor,[<footnote.reference refid="I78b6aa6274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] or on the sound of the motor alone.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78b6aa6374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Even if the witness had only “a glimpse” of the vehicle, he may state an opinion as to speed, and it should go to the jury.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78b6d17074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] In several Georgia cases, a lay witness gave an opinion about vehicle speed, without actually seeing the vehicle, based on factors that he observed at the vehicle.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78b6d17174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>An expert may base his opinion on an examination of facts at the scene of a wreck.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78b6d17274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1970135188" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idcc6c63274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Bartow County School Dist. v. Weaver</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I78b6d17374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] an expert reconstructed a vehicle collision in his testimony before the jury.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1976135564" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idcc7898274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Dual S. Enterprises, Inc. v. Webb</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I78b6f88074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>
						<?page no="200"?>] the Georgia Court of Appeals reviewed the use of opinion testimony regarding speed in a case in which an expert witness testified about the “safe speed” for a truck to go around a curve, a lay witness testified about the collision point of impact based on factors he observed at the scene, and another expert witness testified about the point of impact based on his observations at the scene and, in part, upon measurements made by others.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
